Q11_1:
[Faculty Session] Learning to See (Kathryn Boudett & David Rease Jr.)

In this session, we discussed why it is important to examine instruction, then focused on learning strategies for maintaining a relentless focus on evidence when observing classrooms.  We practiced taking specific and descriptive notes when by watching a video, and used the Objectivity/Specificity Matrix as a framework for thinking about observation data. We concluded by discussing the importance of paying attention to task when observing practice, and watched the video a second time with task top of mind. - Importance of Topic

Q10:
To be truthful, the rock, paper, scissors activity was incredibly stressful for me. I was unaware that the pathway for learning would become so incredibly loud, and had I known, I would have liked the opportunity to opt out of this activity. Although I have no issue with this activity, for me, the noise triggered significant distress. I was quite shaken afterwards, and it took me some time to recover and reengage in the learning. 
I know this is a great activity with students, but I am mindful in a school setting of noise levels, especially for students with autism, special needs, and/or backgrounds of trauma. On a positive note, this activity reminded me of how these students may feel in this situation, and the importance of considering the backgrounds of learners when engaging in unexpected activities.
Q19: This session was amazing. Really got a lot out of this session. The quality of instruction was high - clear and concise. The fact that the team took on the delta feedback really helped my group out.
